(2). (iii) variant of   Mule   with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>. Compare John Meul, 1327 in   Subsidy Rolls   (Newlyn East, Cornwall)."],"variants":[{"name":"Subsidy Rolls","meanings":["English: (i)  see  Broker  . The   MED   notes that the  <i>-o-</i> could be long. (ii) locative name sometimes perhaps denoting a ‘dweller by the brook’, from an agent derivative of Middle English  <i>brok</i>. William le Broker, 1332 in   Subsidy Rolls   (Sussex), was probably a descendant of Anger atte Broke, 1296   Subsidy Rolls   (Sussex).  Compare  Brook  ."]},{"name":"Mule","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Vito, Angelo, Antonio, Matteo, Sal, Carmelo, Concetta, Francesco, Gaetano, Gaspare, Gino, Rosario.","English: nickname, perhaps for a stubborn person, from Middle English <i>mule</i>, <i>muel</i>, <i>meul</i>, <i>moile</i> ‘mule’ (Old French <i>mule</i>). See also   Moyle   and   Moule  , with which this name may have been interchangeable.","French: nickname from <i>mule</i> ‘female mule’."]},{"name":"Moles","meanings":["English: variant of   Moll  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Catalan: habitational name from any of various minor places called Moles, from the plural of <i>mola</i> (see   Mola  ).","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Meulles (Calvados). See also   Moyles  ."]},{"name":"Mullis","meanings":["English (mainly West Midlands):","variant of   Moule  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","habitational name from Mowlish Farm in Kenton (Devon). The placename appears to mean ‘farm of the mules’, from the genitive plural form of Old English <i>mūl</i> ‘mule’ + <i>hīwisc</i> ‘family, measure of land that would support a family’."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":16,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"James Mulys was born in 1366, in Cornwall, England. He had at least 1 daughter with Isabella Attwode. He died in 1396, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1366–1396":"1366–1396","1361–1399":"1361–1399","1380–1426":"1380–1426","1426":"1426","1366":"1366","1399":"1399","1396":"1396","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Swimbridge, Devon, England":"Swimbridge, Devon, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1366–1396":"1366–1396","1361–1399":"1361–1399","1380–1426":"1380–1426","1426":"1426","1366":"1366","1399":"1399","1396":"1396","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Swimbridge, Devon, England":"Swimbridge, Devon, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1366–1396":"1366–1396","1361–1399":"1361–1399","1380–1426":"1380–1426","1426":"1426","1366":"1366","1399":"1399","1396":"1396","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Swimbridge, Devon, England":"Swimbridge, Devon, Angleterre","Cornwall, England":"Cornouailles, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"James Mulys est né en 1366, à Cornouailles, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Isabella Attwode. Il est décédé en 1396, à Cornouailles, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, à l’âge de 30 ans."},"de":{"1366–1396":"1366–1396","1361–1399":"1361–1399","1380–1426":"1380–1426","1426":"1426","1366":"1366","1399":"1399","1396":"1396","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Swimbridge, Devon, England":"Swimbridge, Devon, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"James Mulys wurde 1366 in Cornwall, England geboren. Er hatte mit Isabella Attwode mindestens 1 Tochter. Er starb 1396 im Alter von 30 Jahren in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom."},"ht":{"1366–1396":"1366–1396","1361–1399":"1361–1399","1380–1426":"1380–1426","1426":"1426","1366":"1366","1399":"1399","1396":"1396","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Swimbridge, Devon, England":"Swimbridge, Devon, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Angletè, United Kingdom"},"hu":{"1366–1396":"1366–1396","1361–1399":"1361–1399","1380–1426":"1380–1426","1